## Context

Supersedes 0003 (closed). 0003 proposed auto-generating test stubs
from /verify blockers. Rejected because:

- /verify is a per-PR gate — the wrong layer for test generalization.
- Auto-generated stubs from review prose risk encoding the letter of
  the comment, not the underlying invariant.
- TDD already asks the author to write the test; stubs are a crutch
  for authors skipping the red step.

The TDD accumulation concern still stands: a bugfix that doesn't
leave a standing test behind can regress silently in unrelated future
PRs. /celebrate is the reflective layer — post-merge, with distance
from the incident — and is the natural place to ask whether a bug
reveals a class worth guarding.

## Actions

1. Patch `skills/celebrate/SKILL.md`: when the merged work includes
   a bugfix, prompt the author "does this bug reveal a class worth a
   standing test?"
2. If yes, open a follow-up ticket for the regression test. The test
   lands as its own reviewed change, not smuggled into the fix PR.
3. Keep it a prompt, not an enforced step. Author judgment decides
   whether the bug has a generalizable shape. No scaffolding, no
   auto-written assertions.

## Test

Run /celebrate after a recent bugfix merge. Expect the reflection
prompt to fire and, on acceptance, produce a new ticket referencing
the fix PR.

## Exit criteria

- /celebrate surfaces the bug-class question on bugfix merges.
- Accepting the prompt creates a follow-up ticket (not an auto test).
- Declining is silent — no nagging, no markers on the PR.
- 0003 referenced in this ticket's context as superseded.
